Saturday August 31st 2013 9:30 am -04:00,Ramon - Try to break the problem down using the examples and the information provided as part of the assignment. We are given the hours minutes and seconds and we need to somehow combine them. What do we know? We are given the number of hours so we just have to add the minutes and seconds to that number. There is a precondition that tells us the minutes will be less than 60 so never making more hours and seconds will always be less than 60 so never making more minutes. All of this means that we already know the number of hours we just have to figure out how to deal with the fractions (or parts of the hour).What do we know about time? We know that 15 minutes is a quarter of an hour. A quarter (1/4) in float is 0.25. That looks a lot like the first example. If we want a quarter of an hour perhaps we could express it as something like 15/60 (60 minutes in an hour)?You can apply the same thinking to seconds.To get your final result you want to think about what mathematical operator allows your to add your results together., Unresolved,1
